*Loebel v. Loebel*, 77 Mass. App. Ct. 74.relevant_excerpt:
“When determining child custody awards in general, or modifications of custody awards based on changed circumstances, the guiding principle always has been the best interests of the children. . . .
…
‘General Laws c. 208, § 28, authorizes the court to “make a judgment modifying its earlier judgment as to the care and custody of the minor children of the parties provided that the court finds that a material and substantial change in the circumstances of the parties has occurred and the judgment of modification is necessary in the best interests of the children.”’ … ‘physical force within the family is both intolerable… and a child… suffers a distinctly grievous kind of harm.’”}
